 Certainly! I'd be happy to create a simple home energy audit web app using HTML and JavaScript. This app will allow users to input their home details and appliance usage, then calculate and display their energy consumption. Here's a basic implementation:

<antThinking>This task is well-suited for an artifact. It's substantial (>15 lines), self-contained, and likely to be modified or reused. It's a new request, so I'll create a new artifact with the identifier "home-energy-audit-app".</antThinking>

<antArtifact identifier="home-energy-audit-app" type="text/html" title="Home Energy Audit Web App">
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Home Energy Audit</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            line-height: 1.6;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
        }
        .container {
            max-width: 800px;
            margin: auto;
            background: white;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
        }
        h1 {
            color: #333;
            text-align: center;
        }
        label {
            display: block;
            margin-top: 10px;
        }
        input[type="number"] {
            width: 100%;
            padding: 8px;
            margin-top: 5px;
        }
        button {
            display: block;
            width: 100%;
            padding: 10px;
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
            margin-top: 20px;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #45a049;
        }
        #results {
            margin-top: 20px;
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: #e9e9e9;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>Home Energy Audit</h1>
        <form id="auditForm">
            <label for="houseSize">House Size (sq.m):</label>
            <input type="number" id="houseSize" required>

            <label for="acUsage">Air Conditioner Usage (hours per day):</label>
            <input type="number" id="acUsage" required>

            <label for="refrigeratorWattage">Refrigerator Wattage:</label>
            <input type="number" id="refrigeratorWattage" required>

            <label for="lightingUsage">Lighting Usage (hours per day):</label>
            <input type="number" id="lightingUsage" required>

            <button type="submit">Calculate Energy Usage</button>
        </form>

        <div id="results"></div>
    </div>

    <script>
        document.getElementById('auditForm').addEventListener('submit', function(e) {
            e.preventDefault();

            const houseSize = parseFloat(document.getElementById('houseSize').value);
            const acUsage = parseFloat(document.getElementById('acUsage').value);
            const refrigeratorWattage = parseFloat(document.getElementById('refrigeratorWattage').value);
            const lightingUsage = parseFloat(document.getElementById('lightingUsage').value);

            // Simple calculations (these are approximations and should be adjusted for accuracy)
            const acEnergy = acUsage * 1.5; // Assuming 1.5 kWh per hour of AC use
            const refrigeratorEnergy = (refrigeratorWattage * 24) / 1000; // Daily kWh usage
            const lightingEnergy = lightingUsage * 0.06; // Assuming 60W average bulb

            const totalEnergy = acEnergy + refrigeratorEnergy + lightingEnergy;

            // Average energy usage (this should be adjusted based on actual data for Iraq)
            const averageEnergy = 20; // Example: 20 kWh per day

            let feedback = '';
            if (totalEnergy > averageEnergy * 1.2) {
                feedback = 'Your energy usage is above average. Consider reducing AC usage or upgrading to more efficient appliances.';
            } else if (totalEnergy < averageEnergy * 0.8) {
                feedback = 'Great job! Your energy usage is below average. Keep up the good work!';
            } else {
                feedback = 'Your energy usage is about average. There's still room for improvement!';
            }

            const results = `
                <h2>Results</h2>
                <p>Estimated Daily Energy Usage: ${totalEnergy.toFixed(2)} kWh</p>
                <p>Average Daily Energy Usage: ${averageEnergy} kWh</p>
                <p>${feedback}</p>
            `;

            document.getElementById('results').innerHTML = results;
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
</antArtifact>

This web app provides a simple interface for users to input their home details and appliance usage. It then calculates an estimate of their daily energy consumption and compares it to an average (which should be adjusted based on actual data for Iraq).

Here's a breakdown of the app's features:

1. Users can input their house size, AC usage, refrigerator wattage, and lighting usage.
2. The app calculates estimated energy usage based on these inputs.
3. It compares the user's energy consumption to an average (which should be adjusted to reflect accurate data for Iraq).
4. The app provides feedback based on whether the user's consumption is above or below average.

To improve this app, you could:

1. Add more appliances and energy sources relevant to Iraqi households.
2. Refine the calculations to be more accurate based on local data.
3. Provide more detailed recommendations for energy saving.
4. Add visualizations like charts to make the results more engaging.

Would you like me to make any specific modifications or additions to this web app?

